nd a bureaucracy\non its hands excessive even for its\nformer size, it is faced with what\nappears to be an almost insolvable\nproblem.\n\"The taxable capacity of Tur\nkey's population, impoverished\nthrough long periods of war and\ntinsettlement, is reduced to the\nvanishing point and, up to the\npresent, the foreign element the\nonly one able to bear the burden\nhas been exempt, i Nor are the\ngovernment finances alone in a\ncondition of bankrutpcy. The city\nit Constantinople is likewise re\nduced to dire straights and is un\nable to provide 'properly for some\nof the most essential public serv\nices, with the result that the city\npresents a neglected appearance.\n\"And one of the most Important\nfeatures in the Turkish situation is\nthe gradual recognition that the\nfollowers of Mustapha Kemal rep\nresent economically, strategically\nand politically a force that has to\nbe reckoned with in any settlement\narrived at with Turkey. Constanti\nnople is incapable of separate ex\nistence, severed from the produc\ning parts of the Turkish dominions.\nParticipation Of the national dele\ngates at the conferences now being\nheld in London may therefore be\n'reenrrieit rx a honeful development.\n\"From a commercial point of\n.view present conditions! in con\nstantlnople present a more or less\ncomplete analogy to other parts of\ntha .world, possibly in somewhat\npi crwte4 (oris, dut to tba con\nplete exhaustion or inaccessibility\nof Its chief outlets. Losses Incurred\nby the trading community have\nbeen very severe, but failures of\nimportance have, in comparison\nwith other markets, been few In\nnumber mainly due to the assist\nance rendered perforce by the\nbanks. As a, result, however, the\nlocal banking position is strained.\nPrcstitfo of I'niUtl SUiMti.\n\"No recovery can reasonably be\nexpected until the political horizon\nclears world conditions generally\nimprove and until the natural mar\nkets, both of supply and of con\nsumption,' are again accessible to\nthe merchants of. Constantinople.\nWhen this is achieved it seeijis in\nevitable that Constantinople will\nagain occupy its former position as\nthe distributing and banking cenr\nter of the Near East, for, as Gibbon\nputs it: (The single spot united the\nprospects of beauty, safety and of\nwealth formed by nature for the\ncenter and capital of a great mon\narchy.' \"It is gratifying to find that the\nprestige of the XTnited States' and\nthe acknowledged soundness of its\nbanking system is commanding the\nconfidence of the public, not mere\nly in Turkey but in a wide range\nof surrounding territory. With a\nreturn of prosperity to those sorely\ntried countries, American business\ninterests, assisted by this outpost\nof American, banking enterprise\nand by the transportation facilities\nprovided through the foresight of\nthe carriers, should share to their\nGRASS IN SHELTERED\nPLACES IS GROWING\n(Spoclsl Correnpondxnr to The Journal.\nTucumcari, N. M., March 13.\nThe tourist season has opened. A\nnumber of cars pass through the\ncity each day.- The season has\nopened six weeks earlier than in\nformer years for tourist travel\nthrough this section.\nNicolas Tafoya, for sixty years a\nresident of this part of the state,\nsays this1 winter is unprecedented\nIn the history of this section. Grass\nin sheltered places can be found\ngrowing several inches In height.\nJ. L. Dupuy and wife of Houston,\nTex., and R. L. Dupuy of Brecken\nridge, are oil people who are stop\nping In the city for a day or two.\nThe Dupuys will spend the next\nsixty days touring points of interest\nin the state.. v\nOFFICERS ELECTED V i\nBY ELKS OF RATON\nRaton, N. M. March 18. The\nfollowing officers of the Raton\nElks were elected: Exalted ruler,\nJ. D. Guthrie; esteemed leading\nknight, C. J. Humphreys; esteemed\nloyal knight, A. H.- Darden; es\nteemed lecturing knight, W, D.\nPlerson; secretary; Joseph- Cencel;\ntreasurer, C. N. Blackwell; trustee\nfor three years, E. G. Twitty;\ntrustee for two years, L. C. yfhlte.\nThere were an exceptionally larg\nnumber of Elks present at the\nmeeting. i\nOn March 26 the Elks will take\nin a class of approximately thirty\ncandidates. The Elk are very\nactive here, there being another\nlarge group to be initiated in a\nvery short time.\nAdvertise in the Morn-\nSPRINGER\nMr. and Mrs. J. 0. Geyer and\nMrs. Studebaker have returned\nfrom a visit to Las Vegas.\nEarl Pointer has gone to Daw\nson, where he has secured a Job.\nMrs. E. W. Bmith was the guest\nof Mrs. Al Hanson during the last\nof the week.\nMrs. Al Lewis has gone to Kan\nsas City, where she will remain for\nsome time.\nMr. Hart, a veteran of the civil\nwar, died at Colmore Wednesday\nand was buried there the following\nday. Deceased was 86 years old.\nMrs. Hartensteln entertained the\nSwastika club last Wednesday.\nBridge was played, Miss Kloers\nheim securing the highest score. A\ndelicious salad course was served.\nMrs. Ralph Coddinghan has re\nturned from Trinidad.\nIrwin FloersheirA was in Roy\nduring the week visiting his moth\ner, who has been quite ill.\nMr. Reynolds, expert account\nant, from Raton was in Springer\nduring the week in connection with\nthe auditing of the city books. The\nSpringer Ladies' Aid was enter\ntained by Mesdames Beneweis and\nMaston and Beneweis at the home\nof, Mrs. Kimball last Thursday.\nW. A, Dow of Colmore and\nFrank Saubel of Sweetwater enter\ntained tbe Masons here Friday\nnight.\nDUKE CITY RECORDED\n82 OF THE POSSIBLE\nSUNSHINELAST MONTH\nSanta Fe, March 13. February\nwas a mild, dry month, according\nto the weather bureau report Just\nt.ssued here.- Practically all parts\nof the state shared in the excess of\ntemperature, and northwest coun\nties averaged 4 to 6 degrees above\nthe normal. On the other hand a\nfew southern stations showed a\nsmall deficiency. Fairly warm\nweather prevailed at the beginning\nof the month and warm periods\nfollowed on the 12th to 15th and\n21st to the close. Cool periods oc\ncurred on the 7th to 9th and 17th\nto 20th. The 25th was probably\nthe warmest day of the month and\nthe 8th the coldest, although the\n19th proved the coldest in many\ndistricts.\nThe precipitation of the month\nwas light throughout the state,\nFairlv large areas in Guadalupe,\nLincoln, Otero, eastern Socorro and\nnorth and east Sierra had less tnan\na tenth of an inch, while the gen\neral average for the state was less\nthan a half \"inch. Oeneral periods\nof precipitation occurred on the\n-7th and I718th, while scattered\nshowers fell on the l-2nd and in\nthe far south bathe Jt-28th. Some\nsnow occurred out the warmth of\nthe month quickly cleared all lower\nlevels and less stored depth remain\ned over the mountain areas than\nat the close of January.\nThe general warmth was Iavo-\nable for stock which continued in\ngood condition, but the dryness\ncaused ranges, to deteriorate and\nthey were poorln many districts.\nPreliminary farm work and early\ngardening were well under way In\nsouthern valleys by the close of the\nmonth, and early fruits were\nblooming, although killing .frosts\nrerf oommon until the 2qih.\"v\ncent of the possible sunshine, or\n250 hours; Santa Ke 78 per cent of\nthe possible, or 239 hours; Roswell\n76 per cent of the possible, and\nAmartllo 88 per cent of the possible.\nFORMER RESIDENTS OF\nTyCUMCARIJIAKE GOOD\n(Special Correnpondrnce to Th Journal.)\nTucumcari, N. M., March 13.\nKenneth Chorley. who came hero\nseven years ago and wonted for\nthree years as clerk under V. 8.\nDevor, terminal agent at this place,\nhas made good. Chorley went into\nservice as superintendent of the\nnorthern division of the Detroit,\nToledo Irpnton railway on\nMarch 6.\nThe Detroit Toledo Ironton\nwas owned by the Phelps-Dodge\npeople until recently, when it waa\npurchased by Henry Ford. Suiter\ncrivnfi credit to\ninifniirni kuvhj e\nhis Tucumcari boss in a letter writ\nten March 2, He says: \"Seven\nyears ago I was a yard clerk In\nTucumcari getting 180 a month.\nKvery time I get a promotion I\nthink of you. First because you\nare the. manwove me my\nfoundation anu ,hi\nand any access 1 ev hfve in this\ngame I can\nbKed Carrol, who received his\ntraining in clerical work un\nder Mr. Devor at this\nwho has until recenuy KV,rpVe.\nthe Dixie Oil compa.., wMle\nport, La- rer Vt time ago. A. M.\npromotion a short time ag un.\nMcCorkle, also a and\nthe Dixie people at a salary oi t\nper mnni.ii.\nMrS.A.H.raymh\nRan Francisco,\nM. A. H. P-y-on. wife of Albert\nH. Payson, vice p.\"\" -rorthwestern\nPaci ic Railroad (i(;n(\nFb Rai roaa cuiui\"i\n?e a Mateo, near here\nnospuai in\ntoday, after a brief illness\nerr THIS oct-t IS WORTH\nMOM\nCut out this slip, enclose with Be\nand mail it to Foley Co M\nSheffieia y address clearly,\nvour name and aaare\nu will receive to return trW\nnuckage containing Foley\" Heme'\nand Tar Compound\ncolds and croup; Foley KM\ntor pains in u -r\" ana\nmatlsm, backache, hi dney\nbladder ailments; and Foley u\nthartio Tablets, a h01?\"0,\"1' a\"or\nthorough cleansing cathr\"0.chei\nconstipation. biUousness. hdache.\nand aluggish bowels. Sold every\nwhere.\nLEGALNOTICE\nADMINISTRATOU NOTICE.\nIn the Probate Court of Bernalillo\nCounty, New Mexico.\nIn the Matter of the Estate Of Rev.\nJohn V. W. Cooney, ecea8ed\nNotice is hereby given that tne\nundersigned was, on the 17th day\nof February. 1M1. duly appointed\nAdministrator of the estate of Rev.\nthe Probate vCourt of Bernalillo\nsuch Administrator all persons\nhaving claims against the estate of\nsaid decedent are hereby notified\nand required to present the same\nto the undersigned in the manner\nand within the time prescribed by\nlaw.\nREV. ALBERT T. DAEUEIt,\nAdministrator.\nState of New Mexico. County of\nBernalillo. In the Probate Court.\nIn the Matter of the Estate of Ad-\ndic L Gill Muggley, Deceasea.\nNMis in hnrphv niven to whom\nit yiv onm-am: That Alvin H. Ger-\ni. ..nHarglcnpil WHS ai-\nuimaii, i'o u'\"\"b'--i iV V\npointed on the an uuy oi ii.\nT-i mill V